<style>
    .gallery {
        display: grid;
        grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(320px, 1fr));
        gap: 30px;
        margin-top: 50px;
    }

    .card {
        background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05);
        border-radius: 15px;
        overflow: hidden;
        transition: all 0.3s ease;
        box-shadow: 0 0 20px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
    }

        .card:hover {
            transform: translateY(-5px);
            box-shadow: 0 0 30px rgba(0, 191, 255, 0.4);
        }

        .card img {
            width: 100%;
            height: 220px;
            object-fit: cover;
        }

        .card p {
            padding: 15px 20px;
            font-size: 0.95rem;
            color: #cccccc;
            text-align: justify;
        }

    @@media (max-width: 768px) {
        .card img {
            height: 180px;
        }
    }
</style>
<h4 style="text-align:center">Welcome, @Session["FullName"] </h4>

@*<h2 style="text-align:center">In</h2>
    <img style="width:600px;height:80px;margin-left:250px" src="~/Content/Images/astroadventure.png" /><br />*@
<!-- ✅ Modern Space Slider -->
<div id="carouselExampleDark" class="carousel carousel-fade slide mt-5" data-bs-ride="carousel"style="width:700px;height:410px;margin-left:210px">
    <div class="carousel-indicators">
        <button type="button" data-bs-target="#carouselExampleDark" data-bs-slide-to="0" class="active" aria-current="true" aria-label="Slide 1"></button>
        <button type="button" data-bs-target="#carouselExampleDark" data-bs-slide-to="1" aria-label="Slide 2"></button>
        <button type="button" data-bs-target="#carouselExampleDark" data-bs-slide-to="2" aria-label="Slide 3"></button>
        <button type="button" data-bs-target="#carouselExampleDark" data-bs-slide-to="3" aria-label="Slide 4"></button>
    </div>

    <div class="carousel-inner">
        <!-- ✅ First Slide -->
        <div class="carousel-item active" data-bs-interval="7000">
            <img src="~/Content/Images/04Galaxy.jpg"
                 class="d-block w-100"
                 alt="JWST1"
                 style="object-fit: cover; object-position: center;">

            <div class="carousel-caption d-none d-md-block bg-dark bg-opacity-50 rounded-3 p-3">
                <p style="color:white">
                    This is the Sombrero Galaxy, also known as Messier 104 (M104). It is a spiral
                    galaxy located approximately 30 million light-years from Earth in the constellation Virgo.
                </p>
            </div>

        </div>

        <!-- ✅ Second Slide -->
        <div class="carousel-item" data-bs-interval="7000">
            <img src="~/Content/Images/black-hole-vortex.jpg"
                 class="d-block w-100"
                 alt="JWST1"
                 style="object-fit: cover; object-position: center; height: 395px">

            <div class="carousel-caption d-none d-md-block bg-dark bg-opacity-50 rounded-3 p-3">
                <p style="color:white">
                    Black holes are regions in space where an enormous amount of mass is packed into a tiny volume.
                    This creates a gravitational pull so strong that not even light can escape.
                </p>
            </div>

        </div>

        <!-- ✅ Third Slide -->
        <div class="carousel-item" data-bs-interval="7000">
            <img src="~/Content/Images/whirlpool.jpg"
                 class="d-block w-100"
                 alt="JWST1"
                 style="object-fit: cover; object-position: center;height:395px">

            <div class="carousel-caption d-none d-md-block bg-dark bg-opacity-50 rounded-3 p-3">
                @*<h5>Milky Way Galaxy</h5>*@
                <p style="color:white;">
                    Whirlpool Galaxy, also known as Messier 51 (M51) or NGC 5194, a grand-design spiral galaxy.
                    It is located approximately 31 million light-years away from Earth.
                </p>
            </div>

        </div>

        <!-- ✅ Forth Slide -->
        <div class="carousel-item" data-bs-interval="7000">
            <img src="~/Content/Images/k2-18b.jpg"
                 class="d-block w-100"
                 alt="k2-18b"
                 style="object-fit: cover; object-position: center;height:395px">

            <div class="carousel-caption d-none d-md-block bg-dark bg-opacity-50 rounded-3 p-3">
                @*<h5>Milky Way Galaxy</h5>*@
                <p style="color:white;">
                    The exoplanet K2-18 b, which orbits a red dwarf star named K2-18.
                    K2-18 b is located about 120 light-years from Earth in the constellation Leo.
                </p>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ✅ Navigation Buttons -->
    <button class="carousel-control-prev" type="button" data-bs-target="#carouselExampleDark" data-bs-slide="prev">
        <span class="carousel-control-prev-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        <span class="visually-hidden">Previous</span>
    </button>
    <button class="carousel-control-next" type="button" data-bs-target="#carouselExampleDark" data-bs-slide="next">
        <span class="carousel-control-next-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
        <span class="visually-hidden">Next</span>
    </button>
</div>



<div class="gallery">
    <div class="card">
        <img src="~/Content/Images/JWST4.jpeg" alt="Nebula Stars">
        <p>The Southern Ring Nebula, also known as NGC 3132 or the Eight-Burst Nebula. It is a planetary nebula located about 
        2,000 light-years away in the constellation Vela. The nebula is a huge shell of gas and dust ejected from a dying star at the end of its life. </p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
        <img src="~/Content/Images/galaxy.jpg" alt="Milky Way">
        <p>This is the Milky Way galaxy, our home galaxy. This type of galaxy has a central bar-shaped structure of bright stars, from which the spiral arms extend. The bar plays a role in the
        galaxy's evolution by funneling gas towards the center, where new stars are born. Our solar system is located in one of the spiral arms, about halfway from the galactic center. </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <img src="~/Content/Images/Hubble-nebula.jpeg" alt="Galaxy View">
        <p>
            The star cluster Westerlund 2, captured by the Hubble Space Telescope to celebrate its 25th anniversary in 2015.
            Westerlund 2 is a massive cluster of about 3,000 stars, located in the Milky Way galaxy, approximately 20,000 light-years away in the constellation Carina.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <img src="~/Content/Images/JWST1.jpeg" alt="Nebula">
        <p>
            Nicknamed the "Cosmic Cliffs," was captured by the James Webb Space Telescope (JWST).
            It shows the edge of a star-forming region in the Carina Nebula, located approximately 7,600 light-years away from Earth.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <img src="~/Content/Images/JWST2.jpeg" alt="Big Bang Era">
        <p>
            Galaxy cluster SMACS 0723 as it appeared 4.6 billion years ago. This cluster is so massive that its powerful gravitational
            field acts as a gravitational lens, bending and magnifying the light from even more distant galaxies located behind it.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
        <img src="~/Content/Images/JWST-Nebula.jpg" alt="Star Formation">
        <p>
            The Pillars of Creation are towering columns of interstellar gas and dust within the Eagle Nebula, located about 6,500 light-years from Earth.
            This image, first captured by the Hubble Space Telescope in 1995, was later re-imaged by the James Webb Space Telescope in 2022, providing a new, more detailed view.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>